Each version of <% fp '.kitchen.yml' %> specifies these options:

```yaml
# .kitchen.yml
transport:
  name: winrm
  elevated: true
```

Test Kitchen connects to instances over the SSH protocol by default, which is appropriate for configuring Linux instances. The `name` option tells Test Kitchen to connect over the Windows Remote Management (WinRM) protocol, which is typically used to remotely configure Windows Server.

The `elevated` option tells Test Kitchen to run `chef-client` as a scheduled task. We need to specify this option perform remote installation of SQL Server, which does not support direct installation over WinRM. When Test Kitchen runs, it creates a scheduled task and immediately connects to that task so that it can receive the output of `chef-client`. This mechanism enables you to kick off and monitor the `chef-client` run remotely, but the installation and configuration happen entirely in the context of the local Windows account.

Next, from your terminal, move to the <% fp('~/learn-chef/cookbooks/awesome_customers_windows') %> directory.

```bash
# ~/learn-chef
$ cd ~/learn-chef/cookbooks/awesome_customers_windows
```

Now run `kitchen list`. You'll see that the instance was not yet created.

```bash
# ~/learn-chef/cookbooks/awesome_customers_windows
$ kitchen list
